thread.title: Prep Roundup Oct. 16

author: MICHAEL APPELGATE Chronicle Sports Writer
title: Prep Roundup Oct. 16
text:
Comments 
MANHATTAN 35, BROADWATER COUNTY 21: The Tigers clinched their first playoff berth since 2012 with the win and will travel to Jefferson next week to play for the District 5B championship. 
Quarterback Alec Nehring threw for two touchdowns and ran for another to lead Manhattan. He opened the scoring by hitting Shondel Connerton on a 13-yard pass. Then, with a 14-0 lead in the second, Nehring connected with Conner Cross on an 11-yard touchdown. 
Cole Visser ran into the end zone from the 3 for the Tigers’ third touchdown and a 21-7 lead at intermission. 
Nehring plowed in from the 1 with less that two minutes remaining in the third for a 21-point lead. Connerton added a 19-yard rushing touchdown with four minutes left, but the Bulldogs made a late charge. 
Two running touchdowns in about one minute gave Broadwater hope, but Manhattan hung on. 
BELGRADE 55, BROWNING 26: The Panthers won their second game of the year in dominant fashion to move to 2-5 overall. No further scoring information was reported, and head coach Eric Kinnaman did not return a phone call before press time. 
Belgrade will host one-win Park next week in its regular-season finale. 
LONE PEAK 74, ALBERTON 12: Bridger Babcock scored five touchdowns in the first quarter to lead a 54-point opening-frame outburst. The Rams added 20 more points in the second before easing up. 
Babcock scored on runs of 38, 12, 14, 34 and 39 yards. Eddie Starz added two rushing scores from 21 and 5 yards out. Starz also passed to Devin Quinn for touchdowns of 28 and 16 and Chase Samuels also hauled in a 10-yard score. 
After giving up a 78-yard kick return touchdown and a 27-yard passing touchdown in the first, Lone Peak’s defense shut down the Panthers for the final three quarters. 
CORVALLIS 61, PARK 6: The Blue Devils tallied 42 points by halftime en route to a blowout. Park’s Rydell Floyd hit Dalton Walker for a 10-yard score in the fourth quarter to breakup the shutout. 
Corvallis’ Wyatt Haldorson ran for five touchdowns, including a 95-yard score. He also found the end zone on runs of 5, 3, 49 and 20. 
The Blue Devils earned their first win of the year, while Park was denied its second straight victory at home after beating Browning last week.
